<div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header">
      <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#expository" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="expository">
        Expository Notes
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="expository" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#accordionWorks">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <strong>Various expository notes from courses, conference proceedings, holiday gatherings, personal reflections, ...</strong> <br>
        They appear in (anti)chronological order.
        Some are unfinished (like many things including this website), but they may still be useful.
      
      <ul>
           <li> <i> Introduction au calcul différentiel quantique et aux idées de la géométrie non commutative </i> <br>
            I organised the traditional <a href=http://www.umpa.ens-lyon.fr/goutelas> week-end du Goutelas</a> 
            in 2018 with Nalini Anantharaman, and in 2019 with Alain Connes. <br>
            For the latter I coordinated the edition of the notes in a special issue 
            of the <a href=https://jmeenslyon.wordpress.com/hors-serie/> JME journal</a>. <br>
            You can access the <a href="expository/2021-10-10_Goutelas_Connes.pdf"> prepublication</a>
            and the JME <a href="expository/2021-10-21_Goutelas-Alain-Connes_JME.pdf"> publication</a>.
            </li>
            
            <li> <i> Survival Guide to First Order Logic </i> <br>
                 These <a href="expository/2020_Survival_Guide_to_First_Order_Logic_unfinished.pdf"> unfinished notes</a> on first order logic
                 were written with, and mostly by, <a href=https://dna.hamilton.ie/tsterin/index.html> Tristan Sterin</a>.
            </li>
            
            <li> <i> Algebras of loops in surface orbifolds and volumes in moduli spaces </i> <br>
            Some almost finished <a href="expository/2019_Algebras_of_loops_in_surface_orbifolds_and_volumes_in_moduli_spaces.pdf"> notes</a> 
            about geodesic currents and character varieties of surface groups.
            </li>
                                    
            <li> <i> Elementary number theory and quadratic arithmetics </i> <br>
                 Various <a href="#"> notes and thoughts </a> on elementary number theory and arithmetics of quadratic forms, 
                 mostly after <br>
                 the <a href=https://pi.math.cornell.edu/~hatcher/TN/TNpage.html> book </a> Topology of Numbers by Allen Hatcher,
                 the <a href=https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-1-4612-9950-9> book </a> 
                 A Classical Invitation to Algebraic Numbers and Class Fields by Harvey Cohn, <br>
                 the <a href=http://www.numdam.org/item/10.24033/bsmf.1329.pdf>article</a> Sur la théorie de la divisibilité by Jean Dieudonné, <br>
                 and <a href=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLoxv42WBtfCBBDXLoytdgIPdQa3hBg_Ux>Salam lectures </a> on Modular forms by Don Zagier.
            </li>
            
            <li>  <i> Géométrie des algèbres de quaternions réelles </i> <br>
                 These <a href="expository/2020_Géométrie_des_Algèbres_de_Quaternions_Réelles_unfinshed.pdf"> personal notes </a>
                 were written for, and in retrospect of, a mathematical week during the summer 2020 <br> 
                 organised with my friends 
                 <a href=https://www.cirm-math.fr/RepOrga/2383/Poster/bellio-da-nobrega.pdf> Felipe Bellio da Nobrega</a>,
                 <a href=https://www.martin-donati.fr/> Martin Donati</a>,
                 <a href=http://math.univ-lyon1.fr/~jahel/> Colin Jahel</a>,
                 <a href=https://www.imo.universite-paris-saclay.fr/~matthieu.joseph/main.html> Matthieu Joseph</a>,
                 <a href=https://mickael-nahon.fr/en-gb/> Mickael Nahon</a>,
                 <a href="#"> Quentin Vila</a>.
            </li>
            
            <li>  <i> Dynamics and classical entropies of Z-actions </i> <br>
                 These <a href="expository/2018_Lecture-notes_Entropies-and-Socifity.pdf"> lectures notes </a> 
                 of a short master course in 2018 by <a href=http://math.univ-lyon1.fr/homes-www/delasalle/> Mikael de la Salle</a>
                 were written with, and mostly by, <a href=https://www.imo.universite-paris-saclay.fr/~matthieu.joseph/main.html> Matthieu Joseph</a>.
            </li>
            
            <li> <i> Birational geometry and Jung's theorem after Stéphane Lamy </i> <br>
            This <a href ="expository/2018-02_Birational_geometry_Jung_thm_after_Lamy"> presentation</a> of an article by Stéphane Lamy 
            was written for my class mates of the master program in geometry.
            </li>
            
            <li> <i> Topology and geometry of curves in hyperbolic surfaces </i> <br>
            The <a href ="expository/2017-08-31_Stage-M1_Topology Hyperbolic Surfaces.pdf"> report</a> of my 3 month research experience in 2017 at Stony Brook
            with <a href=https://www.math.stonybrook.edu/~moira/> Moira Chas</a>,
            <a href=https://www.math.stonybrook.edu/~tony/> Tony Phillips</a>
            and <a href=https://www.math.stonybrook.edu/~dennis/> Dennis Sullivan</a>.
            </li>
            
            <li> <i> Modularité des courbes elliptiques </i> <br>
            The <a href ="expository/2016-07_Stage-L3_Formes-modulaires.pdf"> report</a> of my 1 month research experience in 2016 at IRMAR
            with <a href=https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Pierre_Wintenberger> Jean-Pierre Wintenberger</a>.
            </li>
            
            <li> <i> Symmetries et invariants en geometrie algébrique </i> <br>
            A naïve and short open-ended <a href="expository/2017-03_Symetrie-et-Invariants_opend.pdf"> reflection</a> about Hilbert's invariant theory.
            <!--
            One may learn much more about this and many related topics in the fantastic books: <br>
            by Jean Dieudonné <i> Cours de géométrie algébrique 1 : Aperçu historique sur le développement de la géométrie algébrique </i> (1974) <br> 
            by Felix Klein on the <i> Development of mathematics in the 19th century </i> (1979).
            --> 
            </li>
            
            <li> <i> Etude statistique des éléments du groupe symmétrique </i> <br>
            My <a href="expository/2014-2015_TIPE.pdf"> research report</a> of my TIPE for applying to the ENS Lyon. <br>
            It concerns the distribution of cycle lengths appearing in the factorisation 
            of random permutations as the order of the symmetric group tends to infinity. <br> 
            In retrospect, most of the results follow from Polya's counting theorem, the symbolic method for generating functions, and asymptotic analysis.  
            </li>
         </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

